@Uniswap enables for something called "Flashswaps", which will actually allow for you to do a flashloan and will rebalance all of the underlying funds to be capital efficient almost all the time.

This will help to make funds efficient as frequently as possible for retail.

This allows you to deposit funds into a yield farm for a Uniswap v3 LP, which will automatically focus on optimizing capital efficiency within certain, smaller price ranges, and when the price moves too much in one direction, so will the LP.

Uniswap v3 will actually be less useful for retail because of that functionality, and more beneficial for MMs and people who are constantly moving around their price ranges, constantly working the market.

This does create a weird balance for LPs.

Uniswap v2 grew exponentially because of its' simplicity. LP holders (primarily retail) were able to just deploy capital to certain pools and gain revenue on fees. That price interval was x*k and covered every possible price point.

With Uniswap's new codebase you are able to be *extremely* capital efficient with your LPs. Meaning, you can be selective around the price with which your LP will have liquidity.

e.g. You can choose the price range you want to provide liquidity between $1000-$3000 for ETH/DAI.
